---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="The Three Pillars of Play - Wearthy" description="Discover the ecology of play: unstructured time, freedom to make choices, and environments full of possibilities. Learn how to raise resilient children in a fear-based world.">
	<header class="header pillars-header">
		<div class="container">
			<div class="header-content">
				<div class="logo-container">
					<div class="logo-circle" aria-hidden="true"></div>
					<a href="/" class="logo">Wearthy</a>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</header>

	<main class="pillars-main">
		<section class="hero-section">
			<div class="container">
				<div class="hero-content">
					<h1 class="main-title">Raising Resilient Children in a Fear-Based World</h1>
					<p class="subtitle">The Three Pillars of Play: An Ecology for Human Flourishing</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<div class="container content-container">
			<section class="video-section">
				<div class="video-wrapper">
					<iframe
						width="100%"
						height="100%"
						src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/8cpTDz_-1ls"
						title="How to raise resilient children in a fear-based world | Lukas Ritson | TEDxUQ"
						frameborder="0"
						allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
						allowfullscreen>
					</iframe>
				</div>
				<div class="video-caption">
					<p>Lukas Ritson, Founder of Wearthy | TEDxUQ</p>
				</div>
			</section>

			<section class="seed-metaphor">
				<div class="metaphor-content">
					<h2>What does a seed need to grow?</h2>
					<div class="elements-grid">
						<div class="element">Sun</div>
						<div class="element">Soil</div>
						<div class="element">Water</div>
					</div>
					<p class="lead-text">
						Remove any one of these, and the seed withers.
					</p>
					<p class="body-text">
						Children are no different. They need their own ecology of play—three essential elements that,
						when combined, create the conditions for human flourishing.
					</p>
				</div>
			</section>

			<section class="pillars-section">
				<h2 class="section-title">The Three Pillars</h2>

				<div class="pillar-detailed">
					<div class="pillar-number">1</div>
					<div class="pillar-content">
						<h3>Unstructured Time</h3>
						<p class="pillar-description">
							Not every moment needs to be scheduled, managed, or optimized. Children need time to simply be.
						</p>
						<p class="pillar-explanation">
							In our modern world, we've filled every gap in our children's days with activities, lessons,
							and supervision. But it's in the unstructured moments—the boring afternoons, the quiet mornings,
							the spaces between events—where creativity emerges and self-direction develops.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="pillar-detailed">
					<div class="pillar-number">2</div>
					<div class="pillar-content">
						<h3>Freedom to Make Choices</h3>
						<p class="pillar-description">
							Even if those choices lead to failure. Especially if they lead to failure.
						</p>
						<p class="pillar-explanation">
							When children make their own choices in play, they learn to assess risk, make decisions,
							and live with consequences. These experiences build judgment and confidence in ways that
							carefully managed activities never can. The freedom to fail is the freedom to learn.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="pillar-detailed">
					<div class="pillar-number">3</div>
					<div class="pillar-content">
						<h3>Environments Full of Possibilities</h3>
						<p class="pillar-description">
							Spaces that whisper "what if?" instead of dictating "you must."
						</p>
						<p class="pillar-explanation">
							The best play environments don't prescribe how they should be used. Instead, they offer
							materials, textures, and challenges that invite exploration and imagination. A log isn't
							just a log—it's a balance beam, a fortress wall, a rocket ship, whatever the child needs it to be.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</section>

			<section class="insight-section">
				<div class="insight-card">
					<h2>From Protecting to Overprotecting</h2>
					<p class="insight-text">
						We've shifted from protecting our children to overprotecting them. We've created a fear-based
						world where the very experiences that build resilience—challenge, risk, even disappointment—are
						seen as threats to avoid rather than gifts to embrace.
					</p>
					<p class="insight-text">
						But here's what I've learned from a decade of creating play spaces: when children overcome
						challenges independently, they don't just build physical strength. They build something far
						more valuable—a refuge of mastery that no one can take away.
					</p>
				</div>
			</section>

			<section class="mastery-section">
				<h2>Building a Refuge of Mastery</h2>
				<div class="mastery-grid">
					<div class="mastery-card">
						<h3>Physical Competence</h3>
						<p>
							When children climb, balance, and swing, they develop body awareness and coordination.
							But more importantly, they learn to trust their own capabilities.
						</p>
					</div>

					<div class="mastery-card">
						<h3>Emotional Resilience</h3>
						<p>
							Through play challenges, children experience setbacks in a safe context. They learn that
							failure isn't final and that persistence pays off.
						</p>
					</div>

					<div class="mastery-card">
						<h3>Social Skills</h3>
						<p>
							Unstructured play creates opportunities for negotiation, conflict resolution, and
							cooperation—skills that can't be taught but must be discovered.
						</p>
					</div>

					<div class="mastery-card">
						<h3>Self-Direction</h3>
						<p>
							When children have the freedom to choose their activities and challenges, they develop
							agency and the ability to motivate themselves.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</section>

			<section class="question-section">
				<div class="question-card">
					<h2>How are you nurturing the ecology of play in your community?</h2>
					<p>
						Every school, every community, every family can create spaces and opportunities that support
						these three pillars. It starts with understanding that children don't need more management—they
						need more freedom within safe boundaries.
					</p>
					<p>
						At Wearthy, we design playgrounds that embody these principles. We create environments where
						children can explore, take appropriate risks, and develop the resilience they need to thrive
						in an uncertain world.
					</p>
				</div>
			</section>

			<section class="cta-section">
				<div class="cta-content">
					<h2>Ready to Create a Play Environment That Builds Resilience?</h2>
					<p>
						Let's discuss how we can design a playground that supports the three pillars of play at your school.
					</p>
					<div class="cta-buttons">
						<a href="/contact" class="btn-primary btn-large">Book a Call</a>
						<a href="/forms/site-appraisal" class="btn-secondary">Book Discovery Call</a>
					</div>
				</div>
			</section>

			<section class="about-lukas">
				<div class="about-content">
					<h2>About Lukas Ritson</h2>
					<p>
						Lukas Ritson is the founder of Wearthy and a TEDx speaker passionate about creating play
						environments that support human flourishing. With over a decade of experience designing
						playgrounds for schools and communities, Lukas has transformed outdoor spaces for more than
						16,000 children worldwide.
					</p>
					<p>
						His work has been recognized with multiple awards, including three consecutive years as QLD
						Play Spaces Winner (2021-2023) and the Australian Institute of Landscape Architects People's
						Choice Award.
					</p>
				</div>
			</section>
		</div>
	</main>

	<footer class="site-footer">
		<div class="container">
			<p>&copy; 2024 Wearthy. The playful beginnings of human flourishing.</p>
		</div>
	</footer>
</BaseLayout>

